The ultrawealthy are feeling emboldened to file lawsuits against journalist=
s and their
publishers, perhaps inspired by Donald Trump=E2=80=99s giddy disregard for =
a free press. In his new book, =E2=80=98Murder the Truth,=E2=80=99 David En=
rich forecasts a dangerous endgame.

William D. Cohan ( https://puck.news/author/william-cohan/?utm_campaign=3DD=
ry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F12%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCR=
IBERS+%283%2F12%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&=
utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )
William D. Cohan ( https://puck.news/author/william-cohan/?utm_campaign=3DD=
ry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F12%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCR=
IBERS+%283%2F12%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&=
utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

A year ago, as was reported on incessantly at the time, the hedge fund bill=
ionaire
Bill Ackman waged a jihad to try to strong-arm Business Insider into removi=
ng a pair of articles about his wife, Neri Oxman, that alleged she had plag=
iarized portions of her thesis when she was a doctoral student at M.I.T. In=
 February 2024, Ackman hired Clare Locke, one of the most aggressive law fi=
rms in the business of suing journalists for defamation or libel, to go aft=
er the publication. In short order, the firm authored a 72-page letter thre=
atening legal
action against Business Insider, which is owned by Axel Springer, the Germa=
n media conglomerate. I=E2=80=99m told that settlement discussions continue=
 to drag on without resolution; the articles about Oxman remain on the Busi=
ness Insider website.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Also about a year ago, David Enrich, the business investigations editor at =
The New York Times, wrote a riveting
piece ( https://www.nytimes.com/2024/04/10/business/media/clare-locke-domin=
ion-voting-fox-defamation.html?utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283=
%2F12%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F12%2F25%29&utm_=
medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12=
a ) about the exodus of partners from Clare Locke in the wake of Fox News=
=E2=80=99s $787 million settlement with its client Dominion Voting Systems.=
 As he went about his reporting, Enrich made repeated attempts to speak wit=
h the firm=E2=80=99s founders, the husband-wife duo Tom Clare and Libby Loc=
ke, who alternatively
ignored or rebuffed his requests. That piece was followed by his fascinatin=
g new book, Murder the Truth.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Many factors have contributed to the recent, precipitous rise in legal acti=
ons against news outlets and journalists, of course. In the always-on, endl=
ess scroll of the digital era, there is way more content than ever before, =
occasionally produced by poorly trained journalists who
rush production and make mistakes. That said, there are plenty of ulterior =
motives on the plaintiff side. After all, you don=E2=80=99t need to have a =
legitimate case to file a lawsuit. The uber-wealthy, for instance, are ofte=
n willing, even eager, to foot large legal bills to challenge the media for=
 unfavorable reporting. For some, you could even say it=E2=80=99s become a =
sport. But the recent successes of one serial litigant in particular, Donal=
d Trump=E2=80=94the Stephanopoulos
affair, Meta paying $25 million to settle a claim, Shari Redstone reportedl=
y hoping to do the same=E2=80=94have only emboldened others to threaten jou=
rnalists with legal action, too, as Ackman is doing with Business Insider. =
They do it because it=E2=80=99s surprisingly effective, especially in an er=
a when many publications are limping along financially and can=E2=80=99t af=
ford a legal skirmish with a billionaire.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

More broadly, a growing swath of the conservative movement is hoping that t=
he Supreme Court will overturn the longstanding legal precedent, set in 196=
4, in The New York Times Co. v. Sullivan, which=E2=80=94along with the Firs=
t Amendment and various state laws=E2=80=94has served as a legal shield for=
 journalists writing about public figures. In the meantime, there is a grow=
ing recognition among those who have tangled with the media, and the plaint=
iff firms that represent them, that
lawsuits don=E2=80=99t need to be winnable to produce the desired result. O=
ftentimes, the mere threat of litigation is enough.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Enrich experienced such threats first hand. After he submitted a memo to Cl=
are Locke soliciting answers to dozens of questions that emerged in the cou=
rse of reporting out his initial article about its internal power struggles=
, the law firm dug in. In a subsequent letter
to David McCraw, the Times=E2=80=99s general counsel, Libby Locke questione=
d whether Enrich was actually working on a piece about Clare Locke and accu=
sed him of engaging in =E2=80=9Cimproper and unethical=E2=80=9D behavior by=
 using the threat of publishing an article about the firm in the paper as a=
 way =E2=80=9Cto coerce engagement [with Clare Locke] for his book.=E2=80=
=9D Enrich assured Clare Locke he was writing a piece about the fissures at=
 the firm. =E2=80=9CEnrich is a
misogynist and a snake,=E2=80=9D Locke wrote to McCraw. =E2=80=9CYou can qu=
ote me on that.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

=C2=A0

In its correspondence with McCraw, the firm also advanced the ridiculous cl=
aim that Enrich was writing the article about Clare Locke as a way to press=
ure one of the firm=E2=80=99s clients to settle an unrelated pending lawsui=
t against the Times. It warned of =E2=80=9Cenormous legal risk=E2=80=9D to =
Enrich, the Times, and Enrich=E2=80=99s
book publisher, Mariner Books, part of HarperCollins, which is owned largel=
y by Rupert Murdoch. Eventually, Clare Locke sent Enrich and the Times a 40=
-page letter, in partial answer to his questions, which =E2=80=9Cassailed=
=E2=80=9D him as =E2=80=9Csexist and malicious.=E2=80=9D Parts of the hosti=
le letter were incorporated into Enrich=E2=80=99s article.

=C2=A0

In his book, Enrich wrote that his =E2=80=9Cbest guess=E2=80=9D for why the=
 law
firm chose the path of =E2=80=9Cintimidation=E2=80=9D was that they had =E2=
=80=9Ctried variations=E2=80=9D of these tactics so many times, and with =
=E2=80=9Csuch resounding success,=E2=80=9D that they figured they might as =
well use them when it was their reputation, not their clients=E2=80=99, tha=
t was on the line. In using =E2=80=9Cwords to change reality,=E2=80=9D he w=
rote, the firm was =E2=80=9Ctrying to murder the truth=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94whi=
ch, of course, became the title of his book.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

I reached out to Libby
Locke for a comment about Enrich=E2=80=99s book, and his reporting ( https:=
//www.nytimes.com/2024/04/10/business/media/clare-locke-dominion-voting-fox=
-defamation.html?utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F12%2F25%29&=
utm_content=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F12%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail=
_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) on her fir=
m. She didn=E2=80=99t hold back: =E2=80=9CEnrich has desperately tried bull=
ying us ever since he was ridiculed in his own newsroom after Clare Locke r=
equired The New York Times to run not just a correction, but a highly unusu=
al
Editors=E2=80=99 Note ( https://www.nytimes.com/2021/05/28/pageoneplus/edit=
ors-note-may-28-2021.html?smid=3Dnytcore-ios-share&referringSource=3Darticl=
eShare&utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F12%2F25%29&utm_conten=
t=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F12%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&ut=
m_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )=E2=80=94running thre=
e full paragraphs and admitting severe journalistic failures=E2=80=94to fix=
 a deeply flawed story that he edited.=E2=80=9D (The story Locke is referri=
ng to was written in May 2021, and Enrich=E2=80=99s name does not appear in=
 it, or in the subsequently published Editors=E2=80=99 Note, though perhaps=
 Enrich felt
=E2=80=9Cridiculed=E2=80=9D anyway. Enrich=E2=80=99s 2024 story about Clare=
 Locke is, so far, free of any noticeable, or corrected, errors.)

The
Dangerous Path
--------------

Enrich told me he set out to write Murder the Truth after noticing that he =
and
his colleagues would get =E2=80=9Cbombarded=E2=80=9D with threatening lette=
rs from lawyers nearly every time they started an investigation of alleged =
wrongdoing by a rich or powerful person. The Times and other big media comp=
anies are able to defend themselves against these legal threats, Enrich not=
ed, because they have their own formidable legal teams, insurance policies,=
 and plenty of resources for the fight. But he began to wonder what it was =
like for journalists at smaller publications, or for
independent journalists with few, if any, legal protections.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

I, too, have experienced this first-hand. I am just off a victorious three-=
plus-year legal campaign, also at the hands of Clare Locke, where I was acc=
used of defamation for a story I wrote ( https://www.propublica.org/article=
/the-bizarre-fall-of-the-ceo-of-coach-and-kate-spades-parent-company.?utm_c=
ampaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F12%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry+Powd=
er+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F12%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dc=
ustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) for ProPublica, in July 2020, ab=
out the former C.E.O. of Tapestry, the publicly traded fashion company, and=
 why he=E2=80=99d been fired. The former C.E.O., who=E2=80=99d been a pre-I=
=2EP.O. partner at Goldman Sachs, sued=20=
me personally, but not ProPublica. He=20=
lost at all three levels of the New York State court system, and paid my le=
gal fees in a settlement agreement after he decided not to appeal the case =
to the Supreme Court, to challenge Sullivan.

=C2=A0

Enrich told me that the wave of legal threats and lawsuits against journali=
sts is =E2=80=9Cthe culmination=E2=80=9D of the efforts by the ultrawealthy=
 =E2=80=9Cand their savvy lawyers=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cchange the playing f=
ield so that it is becoming prohibitively expensive and scary, if you are a=
 journalist anywhere other than at a small handful of national publications=
, to pursue the richest and most powerful people in the country. That is ob=
viously very much in
the interests of those rich and powerful people. They don=E2=80=99t want pe=
ople mucking about in their affairs and trying to scrutinize them and revea=
l some of what they=E2=80=99re doing. Lawyers like Claire Locke and Charles=
 Harder and their ilk are getting very well paid to do this work.=E2=80=9D =
(Harder, best known for representing Hulk Hogan in his invasion-of-privacy =
lawsuit against Gawker, has represented Trump and several Trumpworld figure=
s in their battles with the
media.)=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Trump, of course, is one of the biggest advocates for using the courts to g=
o after the media, and lately has had a surprising amount of success. =E2=
=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s also got his administration to start using the awesome p=
ower of the federal government to make it financially complicated, and unco=
mfortable, for big news outlets to do journalism that might end up being cr=
itical of him or his administration,=E2=80=9D
Enrich said. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s obviously a dangerous path to go down.=
=E2=80=9D

=C2=A0

Murder the Truth is full of examples of the tactics used by the likes of Cl=
are Locke to intimidate journalists and their publishers into curtailing in=
vestigations, or abandoning them outright. He tells the story of a former i=
ndependent journalist, Scott Stedman, who had no formal training per se, bu=
t started his own investigative
website, Forensic News, right out of college. For whatever reason, Stedman =
started writing about Russian oligarchs, including Oleg Deripaska, who quic=
kly enlisted Clare Locke and embarked on an aggressive path of intimidation=
 and legal threats. =E2=80=9CIt became a multiyear campaign against him tha=
t became so overwhelming, both financially and psychologically, that he eve=
ntually gave up, and not for lack of fighting,=E2=80=9D Enrich told me. =E2=
=80=9CHe was ground down into a pulp, and he couldn=E2=80=99t
bear the thought of his life being further consumed in this war of attritio=
n, and he quit journalism.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0

A
Chilling Effect
---------------

Enrich=E2=80=99s book also traces how plaintiffs and their well-paid lawyer=
s are moving closer
to challenging Sullivan at the Supreme Court. He told me that one of Libby =
Locke=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cpersonal goals=E2=80=9D is to persuade as many peo=
ple as possible that New York Times v. Sullivan was =E2=80=9Cwrongly decide=
d,=E2=80=9D that it makes it too difficult to hold the media accountable fo=
r reputational damage, and =E2=80=9Cshould be overturned.=E2=80=9D (Locke d=
id not address this particular claim in her response to me.)=C2=A0

=C2=A0

She
wouldn=E2=80=99t be the only one. On Monday, Don Blankenship, the former We=
st Virginia coal executive who spent time in prison and then tried his hand=
 at politics, filed an amicus brief in support of casino mogul Steve Wynn=
=E2=80=99s legal efforts ( https://www.reuters.com/legal/casino-mogul-wynn-=
asks-us-supreme-court-revisit-times-v-sullivan-defamation-rule-2025-02-07/?=
utm_campaign=3DDry+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F12%2F25%29&utm_content=3DDry=
+Powder+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F12%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sourc=
e=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) to overturn Sullivan. =E2=
=80=9CWe live in a day
and age where the once noble profession of journalism has been hijacked by =
zealots using the flagships of American media to exhort their own personal =
and political biases and opinions to destroy hard earned reputations of pub=
lic figures,=E2=80=9D Blankenship wrote.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Enrich told me he doesn=E2=80=99t think Sullivan is close to being overturn=
ed quite yet, but said he wouldn=E2=80=99t be surprised if the court
eventually made a ruling that would limit the =E2=80=9Cactual malice=E2=80=
=9D standard to public officials only, as opposed to private citizens who a=
re public figures, such as wealthy businesspeople. =E2=80=9CThat could have=
 an enormous chilling effect on the ability of journalists, and the public =
in general, to criticize or scrutinize the affairs of really rich people, w=
ho wield enormous amounts of influence and power in our society and in our =
economy,=E2=80=9D he said.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Ironically, in recent weeks, Bill Ackman has found himself involved in a se=
parate dispute with Clare Locke, much to everyone=E2=80=99s amusement. Earl=
ier this year, in the wake of the December 2024 murder of UnitedHealthcare =
C.E.O. Brian Thompson, the insurance giant hired Clare Locke to go after an=
yone who dared criticize the company for denying coverage to patients. In F=
ebruary, on X, Ackman reposted a note by a doctor
who claimed that UnitedHealthcare had denied care to one of her patients. H=
e took down the post after hearing from Clare Locke, which maintained that =
the doctor=E2=80=99s claim was false.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

But, in an unexpected twist that pits Bill against his own law firm, after =
he took his post down, he spoke extensively with the doctor, who shared her=
 records and emails with him. =E2=80=9CI found her and her story totally cr=
edible,=E2=80=9D he subsequently
tweeted, adding that she was =E2=80=9Ctelling the truth.=E2=80=9D He agreed=
 to cover her expenses in her ongoing legal battle against Clare Locke and =
UnitedHealthcare =E2=80=9Cso that this is a fair fight.=E2=80=9D I have to =
admit, I didn=E2=80=99t have that on my Bill Ackman bingo card.

