ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">A year ago, as was reported on incessantly at the time, the hedge fund =
billionaire
<strong>Bill Ackman</strong> waged a jihad to try to strong-arm Business In=
sider into removing a pair of articles about his wife,<strong> Neri Oxman</=
strong>, that alleged she had plagiarized portions of her thesis when she w=
as a doctoral student at M.I.T. In February 2024, Ackman hired Clare Locke,=
 one of the most aggressive law firms in the business of suing journalists =
for defamation or libel, to go after the publication. In short order, the f=
irm authored a 72-page letter threatening legal
action against Business Insider, which is owned by Axel Springer, the Germa=
n media conglomerate. I=E2=80=99m told that settlement discussions continue=
 to drag on without resolution; the articles about Oxman remain on the Busi=
ness Insider website.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Also about a year ago, <str=
ong>David Enrich</strong>, the business investigations editor at <em>The</e=
m> <em>New York Times</em>, wrote a riveting
<a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2Uktx=
clJLZ0dWak9pTUZSbjhfQVdHVHRJaExpRT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5=
jb20vMjAyNC8wNC8xMC9idXNpbmVzcy9tZWRpYS9jbGFyZS1sb2NrZS1kb21pbmlvbi12b3Rpbm=
ctZm94LWRlZmFtYXRpb24uaHRtbD91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249RHJ5K1Bvd2RlcistK1NVQlNDUklCR=
VJTKyUyODMlMkYxMiUyRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9RHJ5K1Bvd2RlcistK1NVQlND=
UklCRVJTKyUyODMlMkYxMiUyRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTA=
wMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMT=
JhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjo4NDk1MjZ9/08df=
ac686e21742c3ec1baa8d633178c22a8e4acbe5915dffdc632037abcb60c" style=3D"text=
-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;">piece</a> about the exodus of partner=
s from Clare Locke in the wake of Fox News=E2=80=99s $787 million settlemen=
t with its client Dominion Voting Systems. As he went about his reporting, =
Enrich made repeated attempts to speak with the firm=E2=80=99s founders, th=
e husband-wife duo <strong>Tom Clare</strong> and <strong>Libby Locke</stro=
ng>, who alternatively
ignored or rebuffed his requests. That piece was followed by his fascinatin=
g new book, <em>Murder the Truth</em>.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin=
-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Many facto=
rs have contributed to the recent, precipitous rise in legal actions agains=
t news outlets and journalists, of course. In the always-on, endless scroll=
 of the digital era, there is <em>way </em>more content than ever before, o=
ccasionally produced by poorly trained journalists who
rush production and make mistakes. That said, there are plenty of ulterior =
motives on the plaintiff side. After all, you don=E2=80=99t need to have a =
legitimate case to file a lawsuit. The uber-wealthy, for instance, are ofte=
n willing, even eager, to foot large legal bills to challenge the media for=
 unfavorable reporting. For some, you could even say it=E2=80=99s become a =
sport. But the recent successes of one serial litigant in particular, <stro=
ng>Donald Trump</strong>=E2=80=94the <strong>Stephanopoulos
</strong>affair, Meta paying $25 million to settle a claim, <strong>Shari R=
edstone</strong> reportedly hoping to do the same=E2=80=94have only embolde=
ned others to threaten journalists with legal action, too, as Ackman is doi=
ng with Business Insider. They do it because it=E2=80=99s surprisingly effe=
ctive, especially in an era when many publications are limping along financ=
ially and can=E2=80=99t afford a legal skirmish with a billionaire.=C2=A0</=
p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">More broadly, a growing swath of the conservative movem=
ent is hoping that the Supreme Court will overturn the longstanding legal p=
recedent, set in 1964, in <em>The New York Times Co. v. Sullivan</em>, whic=
h=E2=80=94along with the First Amendment and various state laws=E2=80=94has=
 served as a legal shield for journalists writing about public figures. In =
the meantime, there is a growing recognition among those who have tangled w=
ith the media, and the plaintiff firms that represent them, that
lawsuits don=E2=80=99t need to be <em>winnable</em> to produce the desired =
result. Oftentimes, the mere threat of litigation is enough.=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;">Enrich experienced such threats first hand. After he submitted =
a memo to Clare Locke soliciting answers to dozens of questions that emerge=
d in the course of reporting out his initial article about its internal pow=
er struggles, the law firm dug in. In a subsequent letter
to<strong> David McCraw</strong>, the <em>Times</em>=E2=80=99s general coun=
sel, <strong>Libby Locke</strong> questioned whether Enrich was actually wo=
rking on a piece about Clare Locke and accused him of engaging in =E2=80=9C=
improper and unethical=E2=80=9D behavior by using the <em>threat</em> of pu=
blishing an article about the firm in the paper as a way =E2=80=9Cto coerce=
 engagement [with Clare Locke] for his book.=E2=80=9D Enrich assured Clare =
Locke he <em>was</em> writing a piece about the fissures at the firm. =E2=
=80=9CEnrich is a
misogynist and a snake,=E2=80=9D Locke wrote to McCraw. =E2=80=9CYou can qu=
ote me on that.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In its correspondence wi=
th McCraw, the firm also advanced the ridiculous claim that Enrich was writ=
ing the article about Clare Locke as a way to pressure one of the firm=E2=
=80=99s clients to settle an unrelated pending lawsuit against the <em>Time=
s</em>. It warned of =E2=80=9Cenormous legal risk=E2=80=9D to Enrich, the <=
em>Times,</em> and Enrich=E2=80=99s
book publisher, Mariner Books, part of HarperCollins, which is owned largel=
y by <strong>Rupert Murdoch</strong>. Eventually, Clare Locke sent Enrich a=
nd the <em>Times</em> a 40-page letter, in partial answer to his questions,=
 which =E2=80=9Cassailed=E2=80=9D him as =E2=80=9Csexist and malicious.=E2=
=80=9D Parts of the hostile letter were incorporated into Enrich=E2=80=99s =
article.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"=
margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">In his book, Enrich wrote that his =E2=80=9Cbe=
st guess=E2=80=9D for why the law
firm chose the path of =E2=80=9Cintimidation=E2=80=9D was that they had =E2=
=80=9Ctried variations=E2=80=9D of these tactics so many times, and with =
=E2=80=9Csuch resounding success,=E2=80=9D that they figured they might as =
well use them when it was their reputation, not their clients=E2=80=99, tha=
t was on the line. In using =E2=80=9Cwords to change reality,=E2=80=9D he w=
rote, the firm was =E2=80=9Ctrying to murder the truth=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94whi=
ch, of course, became the title of his book.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;=
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">I reached out to Libby
Locke for a comment about Enrich=E2=80=99s book, and his <a href=3D"https:/=
/email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dWak9pTUZSbj=
hfQVdHVHRJaExpRT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5jb20vMjAyNC8wNC8xM=
C9idXNpbmVzcy9tZWRpYS9jbGFyZS1sb2NrZS1kb21pbmlvbi12b3RpbmctZm94LWRlZmFtYXRp=
b24uaHRtbD91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249RHJ5K1Bvd2RlcistK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODMlMkYxMiU=
yRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9RHJ5K1Bvd2RlcistK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODMlMk=
YxMiUyRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlP=
WN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwi=
