9999999997px;"><strong>The
Dangerous Path</strong></h3>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"><div style=
=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">Enrich told me he set out to write <em>Murder the Truth</em> after noti=
cing that he and
his colleagues would get =E2=80=9Cbombarded=E2=80=9D with threatening lette=
rs from lawyers nearly every time they started an investigation of alleged =
wrongdoing by a rich or powerful person. The <em>Times</em> and other big m=
edia companies are able to defend themselves against these legal threats, E=
nrich noted, because they have their own formidable legal teams, insurance =
policies, and plenty of resources for the fight. But he began to wonder wha=
t it was like for journalists at smaller publications, or for
independent journalists with few, if any, legal protections.=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-b=
ottom:0px;">I, too, have experienced this first-hand. I am just off a victo=
rious three-plus-year legal campaign, also at the hands of Clare Locke, whe=
re I was accused of defamation for a story I <a href=3D"https://email.puck.=
news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dWak9pTUZSbjhfQVdHVHRJaE=
xpRT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHJvcHVibGljYS5vcmcvYXJ0aWNsZS90aGUtYml6Y=
XJyZS1mYWxsLW9mLXRoZS1jZW8tb2YtY29hY2gtYW5kLWthdGUtc3BhZGVzLXBhcmVudC1jb21w=
YW55Lj91dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249RHJ5K1Bvd2RlcistK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODMlMkYxMiUyRjI=
1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9RHJ5K1Bvd2RlcistK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODMlMkYxMi=
UyRjI1JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c=
3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJm=
NmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjoyMTE4MzAyfQ/d6628be4220c0044e19c8849=
040a0a06ce8bc47fc740ed9af80ae56fdc47f2fc" style=3D"text-decoration:underlin=
e;color:
#d40000;">wrote</a> for ProPublica, in July 2020, about the former C.E.O. o=
f Tapestry, the publicly traded fashion company, and why he=E2=80=99d been =
fired. The former C.E.O., who=E2=80=99d been a pre-I.P.O. partner at Goldma=
n Sachs, sued me personally, but not ProPublica. He lost at all three level=
s of the New York State court system, and paid my legal fees in a settlemen=
t agreement after he decided not to appeal the case to the Supreme Court, t=
o challenge <em>Sullivan</em>.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;
margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Enri=
ch told me that the wave of legal threats and lawsuits against journalists =
is =E2=80=9Cthe culmination=E2=80=9D of the efforts by the ultrawealthy =E2=
=80=9Cand their savvy lawyers=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cchange the playing field=
 so that it is becoming prohibitively expensive and scary, if you are a jou=
rnalist anywhere other than at a small handful of national publications, to=
 pursue the richest and most powerful people in the country. That is obviou=
sly very much in
the interests of those rich and powerful people. They don=E2=80=99t want pe=
ople mucking about in their affairs and trying to scrutinize them and revea=
l some of what they=E2=80=99re doing. Lawyers like Claire Locke and <strong=
>Charles Harder</strong> and their ilk are getting very well paid to do thi=
s work.=E2=80=9D (Harder, best known for representing <strong>Hulk Hogan</s=
trong> in his invasion-of-privacy lawsuit against Gawker, has represented T=
rump and several Trumpworld figures in their battles with the
media.)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Trump, of course, is one of the biggest a=
dvocates for using the courts to go after the media, and lately has had a s=
urprising amount of success. =E2=80=9CHe=E2=80=99s also got his administrat=
ion to start using the awesome power of the federal government to make it f=
inancially complicated, and uncomfortable, for big news outlets to do journ=
alism that might end up being critical of him or his administration,=E2=80=
=9D
Enrich said. =E2=80=9CThat=E2=80=99s obviously a dangerous path to go down.=
=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;"><em>Murder the Truth</em> is full of examples of the tactics us=
ed by the likes of Clare Locke to intimidate journalists and their publishe=
rs into curtailing investigations, or abandoning them outright. He tells th=
e story of a former independent journalist,<strong> Scott Stedman</strong>,=
 who had no formal training <em>per se, </em>but started his own investigat=
ive
website, Forensic News, right out of college. For whatever reason, Stedman =
started writing about Russian oligarchs, including<strong> Oleg Deripaska</=
strong>, who quickly enlisted Clare Locke and embarked on an aggressive pat=
h of intimidation and legal threats. =E2=80=9CIt became a multiyear campaig=
n against him that became so overwhelming, both financially and psychologic=
ally, that he eventually gave up, and not for lack of fighting,=E2=80=9D En=
rich told me. =E2=80=9CHe was ground down into a pulp, and he couldn=E2=80=
=99t
bear the thought of his life being further consumed in this war of attritio=
n, and he quit journalism.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
